	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=classes.html?class=4&mid=96750731131016>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=4&mid=96750731131016>SOW?!</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=4&mid=96750731131016#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Mon, Aug 28th 8:01 PM 2000</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span><br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Heh... most bards worth their salt call "SOW", "SLOW".&nbsp;&nbsp;That's what Selo's Accelandro is for...<br><br>Anyway, there are a few ways to kite as a bard.  All of them involve using your instruments.<br><br>The simplest is "Bellow Kiting": equip your drum, start Selos, then bellow at your opponment.  Bellow again, then restart Selos.  Run backwards as you do it, you'll still be faster than most mobs (shadowed men or giants will be a bit faster if you're running backwords.)  This can be done effectively at level 12, when you get Brusco's Boastful Bellow.<br><br>Also doable is DDD-kiting.  This involves switching instruments, and you will take some damage doing this.  Use your drum and Selos to speed up, then use your horn and Denon's Discord when they get in melee-ish range.  Just one shot of DDD will work, then run away fast, switch to you drums, reapply Selos, switch to the horn, re-DDD.  Run away and repeat.<br><br>DDD does not stack with itself, it only prolongs the length of it's effects, so just hit it once, and run far enough away that you can change instruments safely.  Hitting the mob with Chains (Snare) or Bellow between DDD and Selos is a good idea too if you're just kiting one mob.  This can be done as early as level 18, though even with maxed brass, I would wait until level 20, as DDD misses a lot at 18 and 19.<br><br>At level 26, you get Appaling Screech and Instill Doubt.  Screech is far better for sticking a fear on a mob, though Instill Doubt, if it works, lasts longer.  At level 26, you can "fear kite", meaning you chain/snare a mob, then fear it and beat on it's backside.  Multiple resists are a raw deal here, but if you're in trouble, Fear and Selos away...<br><br>However, you'll only be fear kiting for one level because at level 27 you'll get charm, and a whole new world will open to you...</p>&nbsp;<br> </td></td></tr>
