	     <form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96749641422142>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=classes.html?class=4&mid=96749641422142>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=4&mid=96749641422142>RE: General Tips for under 20 Bards</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=4&mid=96749641422142#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Mon, Aug 28th 5:00 PM 2000</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span><br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default [2.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>&nbsp;&nbsp; Very good article, though I must say I disagree with the last piece of advice, regarding Brusco's...  As any bard knows, there's not always a good tank around to do the pulling, so who gets to be the main puller?  Yours truly, the platemail-wearing bard.  When you are the desgnated puller, and you are in a group with low healing potential (no clerics, and maybe one druid or paladin), I've found that twisting in more than one buff song can be suicidal...  (Especially if you're having to deal with Lament-resisting multi-mob pulls.)  When I find that I've pulled a heavy hitter (or more...), and twisting group-related songs is just digging myself a grave, I can sometimes simply switch to Brusco's and tone it down, so to speak.  This gives the party a chance to get the stragglers off you.  Once the mob aggro tones down a bit, I can then try twisting in the (admittedly more useful) group songs again.  This will not work in all situations, as the makeup of the group can drastically change the songs needed for group (and the bard's!) survival.<br>   One other thing that must be said about toning down aggro is the use of fisticuffs. Once again, it depends on the group makeup.  You will be doing less aggro on a single mob, but potentially more on the group of mobs if you have a full party.  This is particularly useful when with a good party that can dish damage out well, and in even portions.  (Large melee parties are a good example of this.  Mixing in a few casters for quick nukes and/or hybrids with healing/nukes/snares can be good too.)<br>   Like the earlier post mentioned, you're one of the ultimate group classes.  Make it your goal to help the group!  However, an overeager bard soon makes for a dead bard, and can leave the party short-handed in a dangerous dungeon!<br><br>Good journeys, and have fun!  A bard's life is full of challenge and excitement!</p>&nbsp;<br> </td></td></tr>
