	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=classes.html?class=4&mid=96710342625783>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=4&mid=96710342625783>RE: Four Songs/Multiple Instruments</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=4&mid=96710342625783#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Thu, Aug 24th 3:50 AM 2000</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span><br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [4.67]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Here's a note - you don't actually need to have two inventory slots hotkeyed. As long as you don't intend to select anything with your mouse or basically use your pointer for ANYTHING else, you can do a simpler trick:<br><br>1. Set up your songs hotkeyed in slots 1-5 or 2-6.<br>2. In slot 6 (or 1) put in melee slot #2 (where your instruments go.<br>3. Put instrument number 1 into the melee slot #2 and pick up the second instrument.<br>4. When you want to switch instruments, just use the mouse to select slot 6 - the weapons will switch with a single mouse-click.<br><br>This is a nice trick because you don't need to move the instruments back to your regular inventory (multiple mouseclicks mean more potential mistakes) and you still have 5 hotkeys to work with for songs. The obvious downside is that you have to use the keyboard for EVERYTHING - your mouse is busy holding onto the second instrument. But if all you're doing is playing songs, this can save a bit of wear and tear on your wrist and fingers.<br><br>Whit<br></p>&nbsp;<br> </td></td></tr>
